    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Model Training\n",
        "\n",
        "We implemented two distinct training approaches corresponding to the two model classes. For parametric and machine learning models, including linear regression, ridge regression, LASSO, HAR-RV, decision tree, random forest, and XGBoost, we used a 5-fold cross-validation scheme stratified by stock. Each stock is assigned to one of five folds, and a single model is trained on the four remaining folds before generating out of sample predictions for every time_id in the held-out stock. This process is repeated until every stock has one prediction per model per time_id, where the model was never trained on data from that stock. This design effectively trains cross stock models that capture general volatility patterns across stocks and time_id windows, rather than stock-specific behaviour, and is consistent with large-scale forecasting comparison approaches used in the literature (Makridakis et al., 2018).\n",
        "\n",
        "For GARCH-family models, specifically GARCH(1,1) and GJR-GARCH(1,1) (Glosten et al., 1993), the absence of temporal ordering across time_ids meant a sequential training approach was not feasible. Instead, a separate model is fitted independently on the first 570 seconds of each time_id for each stock. The fitted model is then walked forward unconditionally, producing a point variance estimate for each of the final 30 seconds, which are averaged to obtain the mean variance prediction for that window. Fits where predicted variance exceeded reasonable bounds, produced boundary parameters at or above 0.99, or generated non-finite or negative forecast paths were treated as missing to prevent unstable models from distorting aggregate results.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Numerical Stability\n",
        "\n",
        "Linear regression models occasionally predicted negative volatility values, causing issues in computing QLIKE loss due to the logarithmic term being unable to handle negative inputs. To address this, all negative predictions were clipped to the first percentile of training volatility for that fold. This adjustment affected only 3 out of 428,960 predictions across the dataset, but those 3 cases accounted for approximately 86% of total QLIKE loss prior to the correction, representing a distortion entirely unrelated to genuine model accuracy.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Evaluation Framework\n",
        "\n",
        "Model performance was assessed using four loss functions: mean squared error (MSE), root mean squared error (RMSE), mean absolute error (MAE), and QLIKE. QLIKE is the industry-standard loss metric for volatility forecasting (Patton, 2011) and serves as our primary evaluation criterion. Unlike symmetric metrics such as RMSE, QLIKE asymmetrically penalises under-predictions of volatility, which is appropriate in financial contexts where underestimating risk carries greater consequences than overestimating it (Lopez, 2001). Alongside predictive accuracy, we recorded mean inference latency in microseconds for each model, enabling direct comparison of the accuracy-latency tradeoff across the full model set. Results from prior runs are cached locally so that users do not need to re-run expensive computational workloads unnecessarily.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Part B: Industry Problem Formulation\n",
        "\n",
        "Volatility forecasting is central to a wide range of trading and risk management decisions, including option pricing, inventory risk management, and value at risk estimation (Poon & Granger, 2003). However, translating this financial requirement into a practical modelling system requires careful consideration of both statistical methodology and operational trading constraints, particularly inference latency. Hence, the project relies on both trading knowledge and data science methods to be used effectively.\n",
        "\n",
        "Existing tools available to traders, such as TradingView (TradingView, n.d.), provide historical volatility visualisation and scripting capabilities but offer no mechanism for forward-looking volatility prediction or model comparison. From a data science perspective, building such a system requires decisions around feature engineering, model selection, cross validation design, and evaluation metrics. From a finance perspective, these decisions must be grounded in the realities of how traders actually use volatility forecasts, where the cost of underestimating volatility differs from overestimating it, and where inference speed can be as important as accuracy. Our choice of QLIKE as the primary evaluation metric directly reflects this financial reality, as it asymmetrically penalises under-prediction of volatility in a way that aligns with the risk management priorities of market participants (Patton, 2011).\n",
        "\n",
        "Our tool directly addresses this gap by providing a no-code interface that allows traders and quantitative researchers to configure, run, and compare volatility models across a universe of stocks, with results presented across multiple accuracy metrics and inference latency simultaneously. @fig-workflow summarises the workflow of our product, which we cover in more detail in the Deployment Process portion of our report below."
      ],
      "id": "116788ef"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-workflow\n",
        "#| fig-cap: End-to-end volatility modelling workflow.\n",
        "\n",
        "from matplotlib.patches import FancyArrowPatch, FancyBboxPatch, Polygon\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def add_box(ax, x, y, w, h, text, color, fontsize=9.5):\n",
        "    box = FancyBboxPatch(\n",
        "        (x, y),\n",
        "        w,\n",
        "        h,\n",
        "        boxstyle=\"round,pad=0.012,rounding_size=0.01\",\n",
        "        linewidth=1,\n",
        "        edgecolor=\"#59636e\",\n",
        "        facecolor=color,\n",
        "    )\n",
        "    ax.add_patch(box)\n",
        "    ax.text(x + w / 2, y + h / 2, text, ha=\"center\", va=\"center\", fontsize=fontsize, color=\"#303842\")\n",
        "    return (x, y, w, h)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def add_group(ax, x, y, w, h, title):\n",
        "    group = FancyBboxPatch(\n",
        "        (x, y),\n",
        "        w,\n",
        "        h,\n",
        "        boxstyle=\"round,pad=0.01,rounding_size=0.006\",\n",
        "        linewidth=1,\n",
        "        edgecolor=\"#59636e\",\n",
        "        facecolor=\"none\",\n",
        "    )\n",
        "    ax.add_patch(group)\n",
        "    ax.text(x + w / 2, y + h - 0.22, title, ha=\"center\", va=\"center\", fontsize=10.5, color=\"#303842\")\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def add_diamond(ax, cx, cy, w, h, text, color):\n",
        "    diamond = Polygon(\n",
        "        [[cx, cy + h / 2], [cx + w / 2, cy], [cx, cy - h / 2], [cx - w / 2, cy]],\n",
        "        closed=True,\n",
        "        linewidth=1,\n",
        "        edgecolor=\"#59636e\",\n",
        "        facecolor=color,\n",
        "    )\n",
        "    ax.add_patch(diamond)\n",
        "    ax.text(cx, cy, text, ha=\"center\", va=\"center\", fontsize=9.0, color=\"#303842\")\n",
        "    return (cx - w / 2, cy - h / 2, w, h)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def mid_right(box):\n",
        "    x, y, w, h = box\n",
        "    return (x + w, y + h / 2)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def mid_left(box):\n",
        "    x, y, w, h = box\n",
        "    return (x, y + h / 2)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def mid_top(box):\n",
        "    x, y, w, h = box\n",
        "    return (x + w / 2, y + h)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def mid_bottom(box):\n",
        "    x, y, w, h = box\n",
        "    return (x + w / 2, y)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def add_arrow(\n",
        "    ax,\n",
        "    start,\n",
        "    end,\n",
        "    color=\"#59636e\",\n",
        "    text=None,\n",
        "    text_offset=(0, 0),\n",
        "    connectionstyle=\"arc3,rad=0\",\n",
        "    linestyle=\"-\",\n",
        "):\n",
        "    arrow = FancyArrowPatch(\n",
        "        start,\n",
        "        end,\n",
        "        arrowstyle=\"-|>\",\n",
        "        mutation_scale=13,\n",
        "        linewidth=1.2,\n",
        "        color=color,\n",
        "        linestyle=linestyle,\n",
        "        connectionstyle=connectionstyle,\n",
        "    )\n",
        "    ax.add_patch(arrow)\n",
        "    if text:\n",
        "        ax.text(\n",
        "            (start[0] + end[0]) / 2 + text_offset[0],\n",
        "            (start[1] + end[1]) / 2 + text_offset[1],\n",
        "            text,\n",
        "            ha=\"center\",\n",
        "            va=\"center\",\n",
        "            fontsize=8.3,\n",
        "            color=color,\n",
        "            fontweight=\"bold\",\n",
        "            bbox=dict(facecolor=\"white\", edgecolor=\"none\", pad=1.2),\n",
        "        )\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def add_bent_arrow(ax, points, color=\"#59636e\", text=None, text_xy=None, linestyle=\"-\"):\n",
        "    xs, ys = zip(*points)\n",
        "    ax.plot(xs[:-1], ys[:-1], color=color, linewidth=1.2, linestyle=linestyle)\n",
        "    add_arrow(ax, points[-2], points[-1], color=color, linestyle=linestyle)\n",
        "    if text and text_xy:\n",
        "        ax.text(\n",
        "            *text_xy,\n",
        "            text,\n",
        "            ha=\"center\",\n",
        "            va=\"center\",\n",
        "            fontsize=8.3,\n",
        "            color=color,\n",
        "            fontweight=\"bold\",\n",
        "            bbox=dict(facecolor=\"white\", edgecolor=\"none\", pad=1.2),\n",
        "        )\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 8.6))\n",
        "ax.set_xlim(0, 16)\n",
        "ax.set_ylim(0, 8.4)\n",
        "ax.axis(\"off\")\n",
        "\n",
        "source = \"#fcebea\"\n",
        "process = \"#ffe0a3\"\n",
        "model = \"#cfe8ff\"\n",
        "decision = \"#e4f1ff\"\n",
        "product = \"#b8f0c8\"\n",
        "\n",
        "raw = add_box(ax, 0.25, 4.30, 1.55, 0.90, \"Raw\\norder-book\\ndata\", source, 9.5)\n",
        "cache = add_diamond(ax, 2.90, 4.75, 1.40, 0.95, \"Cached\\nresults?\", decision)\n",
        "\n",
        "load = add_box(ax, 4.10, 5.70, 1.50, 0.62, \"Feature\\ncache\", process, 9.0)\n",
        "clean = add_box(ax, 4.10, 4.70, 1.50, 0.62, \"Clean time\\nwindows\", process, 9.0)\n",
        "extract = add_box(ax, 4.10, 3.70, 1.50, 0.62, \"Order-book\\nfeatures\", process, 9.0)\n",
        "\n",
        "features = add_box(ax, 6.70, 5.70, 1.55, 0.62, \"Feature set\\nor PCA\", model, 9.0)\n",
        "select = add_box(ax, 6.70, 4.70, 1.55, 0.62, \"Selected\\nmodels\", model, 9.0)\n",
        "model_class = add_diamond(ax, 7.48, 3.60, 1.35, 0.82, \"Model\\nclass\", decision)\n",
        "ml = add_box(ax, 9.10, 4.62, 1.42, 0.62, \"ML:\\n5-fold CV\", model, 8.8)\n",
        "garch = add_box(ax, 9.10, 3.22, 1.42, 0.62, \"GARCH:\\nwindow fit\", model, 8.8)\n",
        "\n",
        "forecast = add_box(ax, 11.85, 4.62, 1.55, 0.62, \"Forecast final\\n30 seconds\", model, 8.5)\n",
        "evaluate = add_box(ax, 11.85, 3.55, 1.55, 0.62, \"Accuracy +\\nlatency\", model, 8.5)\n",
        "\n",
        "dashboard = add_box(ax, 14.35, 4.55, 1.25, 0.82, \"Dashboard\\nviews\", product, 9.0)\n",
        "stock = add_box(ax, 14.35, 3.20, 1.25, 0.72, \"Individual\\nstock page\", product, 8.4)\n",
        "universe = add_box(ax, 14.35, 2.10, 1.25, 0.72, \"Stock\\nuniverse page\", product, 8.4)\n",
        "\n",
        "add_arrow(ax, mid_right(raw), mid_left(cache))\n",
        "add_bent_arrow(\n",
        "    ax,\n",
        "    [(2.90, 4.28), (2.90, 1.20), (13.90, 1.20), (13.90, 4.96), mid_left(dashboard)],\n",
        "    text=\"Yes\",\n",
        "    text_xy=(8.40, 1.00),\n",
        "    linestyle=\"--\",\n",
        ")\n",
        "add_bent_arrow(ax, [(3.60, 4.75), (3.78, 4.75), (3.78, 6.01), mid_left(load)], text=\"No\", text_xy=(3.64, 5.55))\n",
        "add_arrow(ax, mid_bottom(load), mid_top(clean))\n",
        "add_arrow(ax, mid_bottom(clean), mid_top(extract))\n",
        "add_bent_arrow(ax, [mid_right(extract), (6.15, 4.01), (6.15, 6.01), mid_left(features)])\n",
        "add_arrow(ax, mid_bottom(features), mid_top(select))\n",
        "add_arrow(ax, mid_bottom(select), mid_top(model_class))\n",
        "add_bent_arrow(ax, [(8.15, 3.60), (8.62, 3.60), (8.62, 4.93), mid_left(ml)])\n",
        "add_bent_arrow(ax, [(8.15, 3.60), (8.62, 3.60), (8.62, 3.53), mid_left(garch)])\n",
        "add_bent_arrow(ax, [mid_right(ml), (11.20, 4.93), mid_left(forecast)])\n",
        "add_bent_arrow(ax, [mid_right(garch), (11.20, 3.53), (11.20, 4.93), mid_left(forecast)])\n",
        "add_arrow(ax, mid_bottom(forecast), mid_top(evaluate))\n",
        "add_bent_arrow(ax, [mid_right(evaluate), (13.82, 3.86), (13.82, 4.96), mid_left(dashboard)])\n",
        "ax.text(\n",
        "    13.86,\n",
        "    4.42,\n",
        "    \"Run\\nartifacts\",\n",
        "    ha=\"center\",\n",
        "    va=\"center\",\n",
        "    fontsize=8.3,\n",
        "    color=\"#59636e\",\n",
        "    fontweight=\"bold\",\n",
        "    bbox=dict(facecolor=\"white\", edgecolor=\"none\", pad=1.2),\n",
        ")\n",
        "add_arrow(ax, mid_bottom(dashboard), mid_top(stock))\n",
        "add_arrow(ax, mid_bottom(stock), mid_top(universe))\n",
        "\n",
        "legend_y = 7.78\n",
        "legend_items = [\n",
        "    (\"Input data\", source, \"box\"),\n",
        "    (\"Processing\", process, \"box\"),\n",
        "    (\"Models / metrics\", model, \"box\"),\n",
        "    (\"Decision\", decision, \"diamond\"),\n",
        "    (\"Dashboard output\", product, \"box\"),\n",
        "]\n",
        "ax.text(0.30, legend_y, \"Legend:\", ha=\"left\", va=\"center\", fontsize=9.0, color=\"#303842\", fontweight=\"bold\")\n",
        "legend_x = 1.20\n",
        "for label, color, shape in legend_items:\n",
        "    if shape == \"diamond\":\n",
        "        add_diamond(ax, legend_x + 0.10, legend_y, 0.22, 0.18, \"\", color)\n",
        "    else:\n",
        "        add_box(ax, legend_x, legend_y - 0.09, 0.22, 0.18, \"\", color, 1)\n",
        "    ax.text(legend_x + 0.30, legend_y, label, ha=\"left\", va=\"center\", fontsize=8.2, color=\"#303842\")\n",
        "    legend_x += 1.95\n",
        "\n",
        "fig.subplots_adjust(left=0.02, right=0.98, top=0.98, bottom=0.05)\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "fig-workflow",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
