      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Discussion\n",
        "\n",
        "Our results show that no single volatility model is universally optimal across all evaluation criteria. Model selection should instead depend on the trader's objective function, latency requirements and asset universe. Hence, we should evaluate models using multiple measures instead of a single accuracy metric. We found that XGBoost produces the strongest overall performance across both the RMSE and QLIKE loss functions while maintaining low inference latency. We reiterate that this tradeoff between inference latency and volatility prediction accuracy shown in @fig-pareto-frontier is the core finding of our analysis.\n",
        "\n",
        "From a data science perspective, our analysis was performed using a static historical dataset containing 112 anonymised stocks. While justifiable in controlled experimentation, the dynamic nature of financial markets is not fully captured. Market regimes, volatility clustering patterns and liquidity conditions evolve over time, so model performance may differ when deployed on live market data. Future work may extend our volatility models to incorporate the most up to date market data and continuously re-fit on live market data to generate the most accurate predictions.\n",
        "\n",
        "From a finance perspective, traders are primarily concerned with the economic value associated with forecasts, including profitability, transaction costs, market impact and risk adjusted returns. A model which produces marginally better volatility forecasts may not produce superior trading performance once these practical considerations are incorporated. Furthermore, since the stocks are anonymised, it is not possible to investigate if model performance varies systematically across sectors, market capitalisations or liquidity profiles. Future work may add more systematic features and incorporate information from additional data feeds such as trades or news.\n",
        "\n",
        "Currently, users are limited to selecting from a predefined set of implemented models. To increase flexibility, users should be able to import their own custom forecasting models and compare them alongside existing approaches. From a modelling perspective, models are traditionally trained using standard objectives (e.g., RSS) when they are later evaluated using volatility specific metrics (e.g., QLIKE). Future work may investigate models trained directly to minimize user specified objective functions, allowing the optimisation of models for metrics most relevant to their application. Additionally, since our analysis was limited to a predefined set of volatility models and hyperparameter configurations, more advanced machine learning architectures and automated hyperparameter optimisation may further improve predictive performance, particularly if the computational power available to a user is increased.\n",
        "\n",
        "# Conclusion\n",
        "\n",
        "In conclusion, we built a tool that helps traders choose the best model for their specific use case, by simultaneously evaluating model accuracy against latency for any combination of assets and loss functions. While the current implementation is limited by static data and a pre-defined list of models, our tool provides a strong foundation for future work. In particular, we suggest future authors expand the product to let traders bring in their own models and integrate the tool with additional or live data feeds. Our product helps outline the clear Pareto frontier that exists between volatility prediction model latency and accuracy, informing traders which model best fits their use case.\n",
        "\n",
        "# Student contributions\n",
        "\n",
        "Eriks Reinfelds wrote most of the front end, back end and caching layer (to ensure heavy results did not need to be unnecessarily recomputed) of the product. He also wrote part of the draft for the final report.\n",
        "\n",
        "Zhan Su contributed to the front end (universe page), the first and second versions of the report code, and figure/table generation.\n",
        "\n",
        "Zhan participated in writing the Results and Conclusion sections of the report. Wendi Ding contributed to backend model exploration, model evaluation, testing, and part of the report.\n",
        "\n",
        "Vania Kumar performed the backend model development by completing data exploration and implementing baseline volatility models. She also prepared and formatted the project presentation and drafted initial sections of the report.\n",
        "\n",
        "Kin Wang Yau contributed to the backend code, particularly the implementation of the models.py file which correctly specifies each of the models. Kin helped ensure the team was prepared for our presentation.\n",
        "\n",
        "Ayush Arora was involved in the ideation phase, contributing to discussions around clustering and individual stock comparisons. He assisted in the implementation of the back end. Ayush designed the presentation template and helped write and polish the final report.\n",
        "\n",
        "# AI Acknowledgement\n",
        "\n",
        "Generative AI was used to assist in planning the structure of this report, editing, proof reading and programming. We note that a first draft of the report was entirely hand written and proofed by humans before being passed over with AI for brevity and to improve the precision of how we worded our ideas. Model used: GPT 5.5 thinking.\n",
        "\n",
        "# References\n",
        "\n",
        "Aquilina, M., Budish, E., & O'Neill, P. (2021). Quantifying the high frequency trading \"arms race\" (BIS Working Paper No. 955). Bank for International Settlements. https://www.bis.org/publ/work955.pdf\n",
        "\n",
        "Corsi, F. (2009). A simple approximate long-memory model of realized volatility. Journal of Financial Econometrics, 7(2), 174–196. https://doi.org/10.1093/jjfinec/nbp001\n",
        "\n",
        "Glosten, L. R., Jagannathan, R., & Runkle, D. E. (1993). On the relation between the expected value and the volatility of the nominal excess return on stocks. Journal of Finance, 48(5), 1779–1801. https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1993.tb05128.x\n",
        "\n",
        "Lopez, J. A. (2001). Evaluating the predictive accuracy of volatility models. Journal of Forecasting, 20(2), 87–109. https://doi.org/10.1002/1099-131X(200103)20:2\\<87::AID-FOR782\\>3.0.CO;2-7\n",
        "\n",
        "Makridakis, S., Spiliotis, E., & Assimakopoulos, V. (2018). The M4 competition: Results, findings, conclusion and way forward. International Journal of Forecasting, 34(4), 802–808. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijforecast.2018.06.001\n",
        "\n",
        "Patton, A. J. (2011). Volatility forecast comparison using imperfect volatility proxies. Journal of Econometrics, 160(1), 246–256. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jeconom.2010.03.034\n",
        "\n",
        "Poon, S. H., & Granger, C. W. J. (2003). Forecasting volatility in financial markets: A review. Journal of Economic Literature, 41(2), 478–539. https://doi.org/10.1257/002205103765762743\n",
        "\n",
        "TradingView. (n.d.). Visuals overview. Pine Script documentation. https://www.tradingview.com/pine-script-docs/visuals/overview/\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# Appendix\n",
        "\n",
        "The appendix records supporting definitions, run metadata, and additional static outputs from the volatility modelling product. These materials are excluded from the main report because they support reproducibility and interpretation, rather than changing the core conclusion that model selection depends on the user's accuracy-latency tradeoff.\n",
        "\n",
        "## A.1 Terminology\n",
        "\n",
        "| Term | Description |\n",
        "|------------------------------------|------------------------------------|\n",
        "| Realised volatility | The observed volatility computed from high-frequency log returns within a time window. In this project it is the target the models attempt to forecast. |\n",
        "| Forecast horizon | The final 30 seconds of each 600-second time_id window. Features are computed before this horizon, while model predictions are evaluated against this held-out interval. |\n",
        "| QLIKE | The main volatility-forecast loss used in the report. It is useful for risk applications because under-predicting volatility is penalised more heavily than over-predicting it. |\n",
        "| Inference latency | The recorded time required to generate a prediction after features are available. This is reported in microseconds to connect model performance with latency-sensitive trading use cases. |\n",
        "| PCA feature mode | A feature mode where correlated raw features are transformed into principal components before modelling. The cached production run used 15 principal components for the fitted models. |\n",
        "| Manual feature mode | A product mode where the user selects specific engineered features directly instead of using PCA components. |\n",
        "| Pareto frontier | The set of models where no other model is both faster and more accurate under the selected metric. |\n",
        "| Cross-stock validation | The validation design where each fold holds out entire stocks, so predictions for a stock come from a model not trained on that stock. |\n",
        "| GARCH window fit | The GARCH-family approach used here, where a separate model is fitted within each time_id window because the original chronological ordering of time_id values is unavailable. |\n",
        "| Cached run artifact | A stored output from the backend pipeline, such as metrics, predictions, feature importance, or stock similarity. The dashboard reads these files instead of recomputing models interactively. |\n",
        "\n",
        "## A.2 Cached Run Metadata"
      ],
      "id": "4c4e49ef"
    },
